    <summary>The capacity of the Bitcoin network continues to grow, which has raised concerns about its ability to support full nodes. However, improving code and encouraging merchants to run full nodes can help solve this issue. While some argue that increasing block sizes is the only way to expand capacity, others suggest decreasing block times or finding a middle ground solution through network simulations. To settle trillions of transactions per day on networks built on top of Bitcoin, scalable SPV-level security could enable individuals to make up the majority of the network. This could be achieved by using a scalable DHT-type network of nodes storing and indexing transaction history.In various discussions among Bitcoin developers, several proposals have been made to increase transaction capacity for Bitcoin. Jim Phillips suggests expanding block size to 20MB, while Thy Shizzle disagrees, suggesting instead to decrease the time it takes to create a 1MB block. Mike Hearn proposes that most existing computer systems and networks can easily handle 20MB blocks every 10 minutes. The debate continues on whether to increase block size or decrease block time, but it is agreed that action is needed soon to expand capacity to avoid this becoming an issue.The Bitcoin community is currently debating whether to increase the block size or decrease the time it takes to make a 1MB block in order to increase transaction throughput and expand capacity. James G. Phillips IV argues that increasing the block size to 20MB will not harm the network as long as most relays are not as slow as his 2Mbps connection. Mike Hearn suggests that most existing computer systems and networks can easily handle 20MB blocks every 10 minutes. However, this proposal is met with concern by Jim Phillips, who argues that making blocks 20mb would slow down block propagation and blow out confirmation times.Despite the different opinions, there is a consensus that action must be taken to expand capacity while considering the trade-offs and risks of different solutions. The Bitcoin-development mailing list serves as an open forum for discussions related to the development of Bitcoin, allowing developers and enthusiasts from around the world to collaborate and contribute to the ongoing development of Bitcoin.</summary>
